Machine Learning Engineer Nanodegree: Detect breast cancer metastases¶

This notebook holds all code needed to implement the solution that is proposed in the document proposel.pdf. It follows the section 7. Project Design:

  • For the implementation of the above described solution I'll first have to acquire the dataset.
  • I then need to write a Dataset Class for PyTorch to read in the HDF5 files as PyTorch has not loader available.
  • The next step would be to inspect some images comparing the patches of PCam and the original images of Camelyon16.
  • For reference I'll provide some statistics of the train/test/validate data, for example the total number of images containing metastases etc.
  • Then I'll use transfer learning to train an Inception CNN on the dataset.
  • Performance (AUC) of this network is shown as baseline for the own network.
  • This model will be minimally tuned to test various parameters.
  • Now the next step to be done is to create the own G-CNN which will be trained with the dataset.
  • This model will be tuned as well as it is not using transfer learning.
  • I'll try different parameters to try to improve the performance of the network.
  • Performance of the different networks will be show to compare them with the Inception baseline.

Dataset¶

Please consult README.md for instructions of where to find and store the datafiles.

PyTorch Dataset class¶

PyTorch is not able to read in HDF5 files natively. But it is easy to create a loader class by implementing the abstract class torch.utils.data.Dataset.

In this section a generic HDF5 Class is used to access HDF5 files. In addition a PCam dataset class is created that inherits from Dataset. This is done to have x and y data bundled in one dataset class.

Two examples exist at

  • PyTorch Data Loading and Processing Tutorial
  • Towards Data Science

The class that implements Dataset is defined in the file utils/data.py.

train_x = utils.HDF5Matrix('data/camelyonpatch_level_2_split_train_x.h5', 'x')
num_patches, patch_w, patch_h, channels = train_x.shape
for wsi in ['tumor_002.tif', 'tumor_003.tif', 'normal_001.tif', 'normal_002.tif']:
    print('---- Random patches of {} --------------------'.format(wsi))
    # open file handle - does not load image into memory
    slide = open_slide('data/{}'.format(wsi))

    # get all patches of the given image and randomly sample four of them
    wsi_patches = train_df.query('wsi_file_name == @wsi').sample(n=4, random_state=4711).reset_index()
    
    # create canvas
    fig = plt.figure()
    
    # display patches from HDF5Matrix compared to the original images
    for i in range(4):
        # get metadata: index of patch, x and y coordinates in level 0 image
        train_x_index, x, y = wsi_patches.iloc[i-1][['Unnamed: 0', 'coord_x', 'coord_y']]

        # plot image from HDF5Matrix
        ax = plt.subplot(2, 4, i+1)
        ax.set_title('H5 #{}'.format(train_x_index))
        ax.axis('off')
        plt.imshow(train_x[train_x_index])
        
        # plot image from original slide
        ax = plt.subplot(2, 4, i+5)
        ax.set_title('#{}'.format(train_x_index))
        ax.axis('off')
        # as we see in the filenames level 2 was used
        plt.imshow(slide.read_region((x, y), 2, (patch_w, patch_h)))
        
        # show image
        if i == 3:
            plt.show()
    slide.close()
    plt.close(fig='all')

The original CAMELYON16 dataset contains

  • a total of 400 whole-slide images.
  • 270 training images (67.5 %) having
    • 160 (59.26%) normal images
    • 110 (40.74%) tumor images
  • 130 (32.5 %) WSIs in the test dataset and no validation set.

Hence at least one image (the first training image) is missing in the metadata.

According to https://github.com/basveeling/pcam they split these images in

We follow the train/test split from the Camelyon16 challenge, and further hold-out 20% of the train WSIs for the validation set.

That can be seen above: Around 32.5% of the images were used for test, the rest is split into train and validate. Of these 270 images 20% are used for validation (around 13% of the total images).

In addition there are no overlapping images in the sets (the merge of the datafiles contains no rows).

Train an Inception v3 network using transfer learning¶

A inception network is trained in this section as baseline of the own model. An example tutorial is available in the PyTorch documentation.

In addition to the torch.utils.data.Dataset child class above named HDF5Matrix a class implementing torch.utils.data.DataLoader is used during the training to utilize the HDF5Matrix class.

Timings have shown that training of one epoch takes around 20 Minutes on a Tesla T4 GPU on Google Cloud when using the pretrained network as fixed feature extractor. If the whole inception network is finetuned one epoch of training takes around 60 minutes.

To avoid having to run the training code inside this notebook training is done in the background. The resulting models and results are stored on disk and transfered so that they can be used inside this notebook.

A pretrained Inception v3 network is used as fixed feature extractor twice:

  1. A network is trained using no image augmentation and using the RMSprop optimizer. But as inception expects tensors with a size of N x 3 x 299 x 299 I have to transform the patches accordingly.
  2. Another network is trained with image augmentation and using the SGD optimizer in nesterov mode.

The next cells show the results. The script train_inception.py accepts a training_name as first input. This name is used to create a csv file containing the results of training and validation phase.

Create own G-CNN¶

In this section a Group Equivariant Convolutional Network is created.

Preprocessing of the images¶

Like in the pretrained networks the patch images will be preprocessed. One step of that is normalization. For that first the mean and standard deviation are computed of the whole training dataset.

Implementation details¶

To have a third comparison available two networks are trained from scratch instead of using transfer learning:

  • A All Convolutional Net that contains only Conv2D layers having the last layer output the binary classification numbers.
  • A Group Equivariant Convolutional Network that contains again only convolutional layers but works with rotation-translation groups.

Code is in train_allnet.py.
